ademy in 2006/07. He made his debut for [[Barisal Division]] in 2005/06 and took an impressive 40 first-class wickets in his first two seasons in the game, with a best analysis of 5 for 61 against [[Dhaka Division]].\n\nIn December 2007, he was called up to the [[Bangladeshi cricket team|Bangladesh]] squad on tour in [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]] as a replacement for the injured [[Syed Rasel]].<ref>{{cite news|author=CricketWorld |url=http://www.cricketworld.com/internationalcricketnews/bangladesh/article/?aid=14178 |title=Syed Rasel Ruled Out Of New Zealand Tour |publisher=CricketWorld |date=December 17, 2007 |access-date=2007-12-29 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204010826/http://www.cricketworld.com/internationalcricketnews/bangladesh/article/?aid=14178 |archive-date=December 4, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/sport/cricket-briefs-18-12-2007/cid/1067535|title=CRICKET BRIEFS 18-12-2007|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22919666/sajidul-islam-replace-rasel-squad|title=Sajidul Islam to replace Rasel in squad|date=2007-12-17|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/160376|title=Syed Rasel ruled out of New Zealand tour|website=www.icc-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> On 4 January 2008 he made his Test debut, he took 2/71 which included taking a wicket with his second ball in Test cricket. In 2013, he made a successful return in the Test side when he played against Zimbabwe in Harare.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22010095/shakib-al-hasan-back-zimbabwe-tests|title=Shakib back for Zimbabwe Tests|date=2013-04-05|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Facebook|sajidulislamofficial}}\n*{{Twitter|of